<table width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" role=
=3D"presentation" style=3D"mso-table-lspace:0pt;mso-table-rspace:0pt;word-b=
reak:break-word;"><tbody><tr><td style=3D"padding-bottom:32px;"><div style=
=3D"color:#000000;direction:ltr;font-family:&#39;Inter&#39;,&#39;Arial&#39;=
;font-size:17px;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:0px;line-height:150%;text-al=
ign:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"margin:0;">Everyone knows=
 that investing in the movie business is a sucker=E2=80=99s bet. So many su=
pposedly sophisticated
financial backers=E2=80=94the Japanese, the Germans, the French, the insura=
nce money, the <em>re</em>-insurance money, the dot-commers, the hedgies, a=
nd lately, the Koreans=E2=80=94have arrived in town with visions of glamor =
and riches. Few have actually made money.<br/><br/>Yes, there are outliers.=
 <strong>Kevin Ulrich</strong>, whose Anchorage Capital owned MGM for a dec=
ade, was bailed out by an overeager Amazon in 2021. <strong>Steve Mnuchin</=
strong>, the investor turned Trump 1.0 Treasury secretary, did fine
on his 2000s-era Dune fund, which has a stake in <em>Avatar</em>, but he is=
 said to have lost a ton on a separate deal with <strong>Ryan Kavanaugh</st=
rong>. Generally, most rich guys leave Hollywood just like wannabe actors f=
rom Kansas: humbled, with less money, but maybe a couple fun stories to tel=
l back home.<br/><br/><strong>Jim Moore</strong> is trying really hard not =
to end up that way. Moore is the embattled C.E.O. of Vine Alternative Inves=
tments, the private equity firm that owns film
finance and production outfit Village Roadshow Entertainment Group. At this=
 point, Village Roadshow has become notorious around town for all the reaso=
ns that have made the past few years so depressing in the entertainment bus=
iness: The high-flying slate finance company, once the envy of the industry=
, moved headlong into producing its own movies and shows, got over its skis=
 a bit, descended into an expensive and protracted legal fight with its big=
gest partner, Warner Bros., and ended up teetering
on the brink of collapse in the aftermath of Covid and the strike-related c=
ontent recession. In December, the Writers Guild issued a rare =E2=80=9CDo =
Not Work=E2=80=9D order against Village, citing scores of unpaid members. N=
ot great.<br/><br/>Moore has struggled to pay bills and has been effectivel=
y sidelined by his board as they furiously seek a buyer for a library of mo=
re than 100 studio films that has been valued at around $400 million. Indus=
try veteran <strong>Steve Mosko</strong>, Village Roadshow=E2=80=99s top
executive, either hit the eject button or was ordered to do so in January a=
fter trying and failing to sell the assets. It=E2=80=99s now a race to make=
 a deal before the whole company falls into bankruptcy. If that happens, it=
=E2=80=99ll mean the death of one of the last independent studio players in=
 Hollywood, and a sad commentary on the state of the industry in 2025.<br/>=
<br/>So of course I needed to give Jim a call. =E2=80=9COne of the goals wi=
th this company=E2=80=94and with Vine in general=E2=80=94is, I don=E2=80=99=
t want to burn any
bridges,=E2=80=9D Moore insisted during our chat. =E2=80=9CI still believe =
in the history of these two companies, and I think there=E2=80=99s a path f=
orward. We can see our way around a couple curves. It=E2=80=99s just differ=
ent. The economics of the industry are different. Everything=E2=80=99s diff=
erent.=E2=80=9D</p></div>
</td></tr></tbody></table>
