39;PuckSerifDisplay&#39;,&#39;Georgia&#39;;font-size:24px;font-weight:400;l=
etter-spacing:normal;line-height:120%;text-align:center;margin-top:0;margin=
-bottom:0;mso-line-height-alt:28.799999999999997px;"><strong>Adventures in =
Co-Fi</strong>
</h3>
</td></tr></tbody></table>
<table width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" role=
=3D"presentation" style=3D"mso-table-lspace:0pt;mso-table-rspace:0pt;word-b=
reak:break-word;"><tbody><tr><td style=3D"padding-bottom:32px;"><div style=
=3D"color:#000000;direction:ltr;font-family:&#39;Inter&#39;,&#39;Arial&#39;=
;font-size:17px;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:0px;line-height:150%;text-al=
ign:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"margin:0;">The Village Ro=
adshow saga is actually pretty interesting and instructive. The company goe=
s back decades,
starting in Australia, and was a pioneer in turning movies=E2=80=94and the =
cash they throw off for decades after their theatrical release=E2=80=94into=
 an institutional investment strategy. In the late =E2=80=9990s, Warner Bro=
s. co-chairs <strong>Bob Daly</strong> and <strong>Terry Semel</strong> nee=
ded money to make the kind of expensive tentpole movies that audiences were=
 starting to demand, so they had the late dealmaker <strong>Jim Miller</str=
ong> architect an arrangement with Village to finance more than just a
one-off movie here and there. Then-C.E.O. <strong>Bruce Berman</strong>, wh=
o came from Warners, helped turn this into an <em>ongoing relationship</em>=
: Village and Warners co-financed the budgets of a =E2=80=9Cslate=E2=80=9D =
of movies that Village opted into and would co-own. That structure seems no=
rmal now=E2=80=94studios regularly bring in slate partners on multiple movi=
es. But the Village co-fi deal was unique at the time and particularly rich=
=2E<br/><br/>Village, for instance, cou=
ld pick and choose the movies it put
money into=E2=80=94and, crucially, the ones it didn=E2=80=99t. And if it pa=
ssed on a Warners hit, a sequel would still be fair game=E2=80=94which is u=
nheard of in today=E2=80=99s co-finance deals, where if you pass on <em>Bar=
bie</em>, you can=E2=80=99t then muscle into <em>Barbie 2</em>. Plus, Villa=
ge didn=E2=80=99t have to put up its money until the movie was <em>actually=
 released</em>. In return, Warners got a reliable partner to take on some o=
f the risk as the studio business became the tentpole business=E2=80=94so r=
eliable that the two sides kept
extending the deal, and it eventually led to more than 100 co-owned movies,=
 including blockbusters like <em>The Matrix</em>, <em>Sherlock Holmes</em>,=
 <em>The Lego Movie</em>, <em>Happy Feet</em>, and the <em>Ocean=E2=80=99s<=
/em> franchise.<br/><br/>Alas, like many arrangements in Hollywood, it was =
a great deal until it wasn=E2=80=99t. Warners hit a dry spell, the matter o=
f which movies were available for investment became more contentious, and V=
illage did a separate slate deal with Sony. By 2015, the company had
accumulated great assets but needed cash.<br/><br/>Enter Vine, which had do=
ne okay in entertainment by picking up various library assets, which is a r=
elatively risk-averse business. But then Vine started <em>lending</em> to c=
ompanies that were producing their own films and shows, like <strong>Luc Be=
sson</strong>=E2=80=99s EuropaCorp and Lakeshore Entertainment. In so doing=
, it dramatically increased its risk profile. <em>Will this movie eventuall=
y open big? Is this show a hit?</em> Long story short, there
weren=E2=80=99t enough hits and the companies couldn=E2=80=99t service thei=
r loans. So instead of being a lender to Village, Lakeshore, and EuropaCorp=
, Vine eventually ended up <em>owning</em> all three=E2=80=94along with its=
 investors, Falcon Investment Advisors and, eventually, the Ontario Teacher=
s=E2=80=99 Pension Plan.<br/><br/>This was around 2017, 2018, when the AT&a=
mp;T people took over Warner Bros. No surprise: The phone company suits did=
n=E2=80=99t love the Village deal. Why, the Hollywood outsiders asked, shou=
ld another company be
allowed to siphon money from the studio=E2=80=99s hit movies? They didn=E2=
=80=99t exactly appreciate that Warners would have never made <em>The Matri=
x</em> if it didn=E2=80=99t have Village as a backstop. At the same time, M=
oore essentially doubled down on his production strategy. He brought in Mos=
ko, the former top Sony Television executive, with a plan to not only manag=
e the Village library and passively co-finance movies, but use the profits =
from the movies that worked at Warner Bros., like <em>Joker</em>, to
produce its own film and TV, too.<br/><br/>Basically, the plan was to build=
 a version of Lionsgate=E2=80=94take the money generated from a strong libr=
ary and pour it back into original productions. But even amid Peak TV, Vill=
age couldn=E2=80=99t seem to get much going. They had a <em>Nash Bridges</e=
m> reboot on USA and a <em>College Bowl</em> revival with the <strong>Manni=
ngs</strong> on NBC. That kind of stuff. (A <em>Tic-Tac-Dough</em> reboot i=
s coming to Game Show Network this year.) But when Covid hit, things
really got challenging.</p></div>
</td></tr></tbody></table>
